description.narrative: Output 2: By the end of 2019, health facilities and communities in Mali have knowledge and capacities for the treatment of Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM), which contributes to Child Health, Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Cross-Sectoral Early Childhood Development, Nutrition â€“ General, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: [Women and children's nutrition]: By the end of 2019, the nutritional status of children aged 0-59 months and women of childbearing age has improved, especially those living in areas with high prevalence of malnutrition, particularly Mopti and Sikasso.

title.narrative: Output 2: By the end of 2019, health facilities and communities in Mali have knowledge and capacities for the treatment of SevereAcute Malnutrition (SAM)

description.narrative: In 2019, no health district experienced a stockout of RUTF and 76 per cent of the expected 190,000 SAM cases enrolled in the treatment program and 90.3 per cent fully recovered, 0.8 per cent died, 7.3 per cent dropped out of treatment, and 0.7 per cent did not recover, in compliance with global standards. A key achievement was the further decentralization of SAM treatment to community health workers sites, where 10 per cent of all admitted SAM cases were managed. | Status:Met | As-of Date:07/02/2020
